---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Hotel Staff Rostering & Operations App | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How a Queensland boutique hotel chain cut scheduling time by 52%, reduced payroll errors by 89%, and unified operations across three properties with a custom mobile app.",

  industry: "Hospitality",
  tags: ["Staff Rostering", "Mobile App", "Flutter", "Xero Integration", "Multi-property"],

  title: "Hotel Staff Rostering & Operations App",
  summary: "A Queensland boutique hotel chain replaced spreadsheet rostering with a mobile-first platform that gave managers full visibility and cut scheduling time in half.",

  heroImageDescription: "Hotel operations manager reviewing staff rosters on a mobile phone in a boutique hotel lobby on the Gold Coast, with reception desk visible in background",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "A boutique hotel chain operating three properties in Queensland — a 45-room property on the Gold Coast, a 28-room property in Noosa, and a 32-room property in inner Brisbane. Total workforce of 85 staff across front desk, housekeeping, food and beverage, and maintenance departments. Operating since 2011, the group has built a reputation for personalised service and was recognised in a Queensland Tourism Awards shortlist in 2023.",
  clientSize: "85 staff · 3 properties · Est. 2011",
  clientLocation: "Gold Coast, Noosa & Brisbane, QLD",

  pullQuote: "Running three hotels means I'm never at all three at once. I used to find out there was a staffing gap at Noosa when someone called me at 7am because the opening manager hadn't shown up and nobody knew who was supposed to be on. Now I can see all three properties in one view and I know exactly who's rostered before I get out of bed.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "General Manager",
  pullQuoteRole: "Operations, Boutique Hotel Chain",

  challenge: [
    "Each hotel property operated its own Excel-based rostering system, maintained by the property manager and shared with staff via email attachments. The roster was typically prepared on a fortnightly basis and distributed as a PDF — which meant it was out of date the moment a shift swap or sick leave request occurred. Shift changes were communicated via WhatsApp group chats, which had become the de facto operational communication channel but mixed urgent operational messages with casual conversation, creating a noisy environment where genuinely important information could easily be missed.",
    "For the general manager overseeing all three properties, the absence of cross-property visibility was a constant source of operational anxiety. Understanding whether the group as a whole was overstaffed or understaffed on any given night required calling each property manager individually, a process that frequently took 30–45 minutes in total and depended on the property managers themselves having current information. When a manager was in the middle of a busy check-in period, getting an accurate answer was genuinely difficult.",
    "Payroll processing was error-prone in ways that caused friction with staff and added administrative overhead to the finance function. Actual hours worked were tracked on paper timesheets that housekeeping and food and beverage staff filled out at the end of each shift, submitted to the property manager, and then transcribed into Xero by the group's bookkeeper. The transcription step introduced regular errors — misread handwriting, incorrect shift codes, wrong employee IDs — that typically weren't discovered until a staff member raised a discrepancy on their pay slip. Resolving these required retrieving and re-checking the original paper timesheet, which wasn't always legible.",
    "Maintenance requests were managed entirely informally. Guests reported issues to the front desk, who would write a note and leave it for the maintenance person — typically on a notepad near the phone, or via WhatsApp message. There was no tracking of whether maintenance requests had been actioned, no record of how long they took to resolve, and no visibility for management of outstanding issues across the property. A guest who called back about an unresolved issue would frequently find that the note had been missed, addressed to the wrong person, or was simply lost in a WhatsApp thread."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The general manager had evaluated two existing hospitality workforce management platforms before approaching All Webbed Labs. Both were designed primarily for large hotel chains with complex enterprise integrations, and the pricing structures — per-property monthly fees plus per-user charges — made them economically difficult to justify for a three-property boutique group with modest technology budgets. The functionality the group needed was genuinely straightforward: digital rosters, shift management, clock-in/clock-out, and a maintenance request log. A custom build could deliver those features without the overhead of enterprise platform complexity.",
    "The Xero integration requirement was a significant factor. The group's bookkeeper had used Xero for years and was not open to changing accounting software. We had prior experience building Xero integrations for payroll workflows, which gave the general manager confidence that the most technically sensitive part of the project was achievable. We also spent time during the initial scoping conversation being honest about the timeline — this wasn't a project that could be delivered in six weeks — and the general manager appreciated the honesty over an underestimate they'd experienced with a previous technology vendor."
  ],

  approach: [
    "Discovery across three geographically dispersed properties required video calls with each property manager and a site visit to two of the three locations. The Gold Coast property had the most complex rostering requirements — the food and beverage operation ran breakfast and dinner services, the housekeeping team had different shift structures on weekdays versus weekends, and casual staff coverage for peak periods needed to be tracked separately from permanent staff. We mapped the roster structure in detail for all three properties before touching any design work, because the data model needed to accommodate genuine variation in how the properties operated.",
    "A key early decision was whether to build a single Flutter app with role-based views or separate apps for staff and managers. We settled on a single app with conditional interfaces — staff see their own roster, upcoming shifts, and a shift swap request workflow; managers see the full property roster, pending shift swap approvals, and the maintenance request queue; the general manager's view spans all three properties. This keeps the codebase unified and avoids the maintenance overhead of two separate apps, while each user type sees an interface that reflects their actual responsibilities.",
    "The Xero payroll integration required careful design work around the Fair Work Act Award interpretation for hospitality workers. The Hospitality Industry (General) Award 2020 has specific rules for casual loadings, overtime rates after ten hours, and penalty rates on Sundays and public holidays. We didn't build Award interpretation logic ourselves — that's specialist territory — but we designed the timesheet data model to capture the inputs that the group's bookkeeper needed to apply Award calculations correctly in Xero, and we built a pre-export review step that flags any timesheets with unusual patterns for human review before they're processed.",
    "The maintenance request module was scoped during a separate conversation with the general manager who, once they understood the system could do more than rostering, asked whether the maintenance tracking problem could be included. We added it to scope after the initial estimate, which created a two-week schedule extension. In retrospect, the maintenance request module should have been identified in discovery — it was a well-known operational problem — but the initial brief had been framed entirely around staffing, and we followed the brief rather than asking whether there were adjacent problems worth solving in the same build.",
    "Total timeline from discovery to production was eighteen weeks. The Flutter app was built alongside the backend API and React manager dashboard in parallel streams, with integration testing across all three in the final four weeks. We used Firebase's Remote Config feature to roll out new features behind flags during testing, which allowed us to test the Xero export workflow against the group's actual Xero account in a staging environment before enabling it in production."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The Flutter app is the primary interface for all 85 staff. On opening the app, a staff member sees their upcoming shifts for the next two weeks, any pending notifications (shift swap requests, roster updates, maintenance assignments), and a quick-access button for clock-in. Clock-in uses device GPS to confirm the staff member is on-site — not as a punitive measure, but to ensure that the timesheet record reflects actual presence rather than a remote clock-in, which matters for the payroll accuracy the group was trying to achieve. Staff can flag a clock-in as a location exception with a note if they're legitimately off-site for a work-related reason.",
    "The roster management interface for property managers is a web-based React dashboard, accessed from a laptop or tablet, that shows the property's full roster on a week view with colour-coded department lanes. Dragging a shift to reassign it prompts a push notification to the affected staff member. Creating a new shift offers the manager a list of eligible staff based on their contracted hours, availability flags, and whether assigning them would trigger an overtime calculation. Managers can approve or decline shift swap requests — submitted by staff through the mobile app — without leaving the roster view.",
    "The general manager's cross-property dashboard shows all three properties simultaneously on a single screen. The key view is an occupancy-adjusted staffing ratio for the current day and next three days — a metric we developed with the general manager during discovery that expresses staffing levels relative to occupancy rather than absolute headcount, which is the operationally meaningful number for a hotel. A property that's 90% occupied and running at normal staffing levels looks very different from one that's 30% occupied with the same headcount, and the dashboard makes that distinction immediately visible.",
    "Timesheet data flows from the app to the backend on clock-out, with a manager approval step before records are locked. Approved timesheets aggregate at the end of each fortnight and are formatted for Xero export using the Xero Payroll API's leave and timesheet endpoints. The export includes shift type codes that map to Xero's pay items, which the bookkeeper configured once during setup and can modify as Award conditions change. The pre-export review screen highlights any staff member who has worked more than ten hours in a single shift, any Sunday or public holiday shifts, and any timesheets that haven't been approved by the property manager.",
    "The maintenance request module gives front desk staff a structured form — property, room number, category, description, and urgency rating — rather than a freeform note. Submitted requests appear in a queue on the property manager's dashboard and are assigned to a maintenance staff member, who receives a push notification on their phone. When the maintenance task is marked complete, the front desk staff member who logged it receives a notification, and if the request is linked to a guest stay, the general manager can see the time from report to resolution in the property's maintenance log. All historical maintenance requests are searchable and exportable."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "Flutter", reason: "Single codebase for iOS and Android staff app — consistent experience across the diverse device mix across 85 staff" },
    { name: "React", reason: "Manager and GM dashboards — complex multi-property data views with drag-and-drop roster interaction" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "Backend API — roster logic, timesheet processing, maintenance request tracking" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Staff, shifts, timesheets, maintenance records — relational integrity critical for payroll accuracy" },
    { name: "Firebase Cloud Messaging", reason: "Push notifications to Flutter app — shift changes, swap requests, maintenance assignments" },
    { name: "Xero Payroll API", reason: "Fortnightly timesheet export directly into the group's existing accounting system" },
    { name: "GCP", reason: "Cloud Run for the API, Cloud SQL for PostgreSQL, Firebase for push — unified Google Cloud billing" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "Staff onboarding was handled property by property over three weeks. We chose the Brisbane property as the first because it had the most technically comfortable property manager and the smallest headcount, which gave us a contained environment to validate the onboarding flow before rolling out to the larger Gold Coast property. Each property's rollout followed the same pattern: manager training on a Thursday, staff training in small groups across Friday and Saturday, and the first live roster published for the following week.",
    "The Xero integration went live in the third payroll cycle after launch — a deliberate choice to give staff and managers time to build confidence with the timesheet approval workflow before the data started flowing into payroll. During the first two payroll cycles, the bookkeeper ran both the old paper-based process and the new digital timesheets in parallel to validate that the outputs matched. There were three discrepancies in the first parallel run, all traced to historical manual data entry errors in Xero that had never been corrected. All three were resolved before the cutover, which gave the bookkeeper and general manager high confidence in the integrated process.",
    "All 85 staff were active on the app within two weeks of their property going live. The two staff members who initially declined to install a work app on their personal phone were provided with a venue-owned device for clock-in purposes — a solution we'd prepared for in advance. Firebase Remote Config allowed us to roll out the maintenance module to the Gold Coast property two weeks before the others, effectively running a real-world pilot before full deployment."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The GPS-based clock-in generated more staff concern during the consultation phase than we'd anticipated. Several staff members were worried that it represented surveillance of their movements beyond their shift, which it absolutely wasn't — the location check only occurs at the moment of clock-in. We addressed this by building a clear, plain-language explanation of how the location data is used and for how long it's retained into the app's onboarding flow, and by involving the general manager in communicating the policy directly to staff before the app launched. The lesson: any feature that touches location data needs a communication plan, not just a privacy policy.",
    "We underestimated the complexity of the casual staff scheduling edge cases. Full-time and part-time staff have fixed contracted hours that are straightforward to model; casual staff have no guaranteed hours, variable availability, and complex Award entitlements around minimum engagement periods. The casuals management feature went through three design iterations before we had something the property managers felt accurately reflected how they actually worked with casual staff. It's now one of the most-used parts of the manager dashboard, but it cost more time than the estimate allowed for.",
    "The maintenance request module revealed a cultural issue that the technology couldn't solve alone. At one property, maintenance requests were being submitted but not acknowledged by the maintenance staff member, who felt that the digital system reduced the personal communication they valued with front desk colleagues. The property manager had a direct conversation about the expectation, and acknowledgement rates normalised within two weeks. Technology can create visibility, but changing ingrained working habits still requires active management."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Eight months after launch, the group asked us to add a guest feedback integration. When a guest checks out, a simple one-question SMS survey is triggered asking about their stay; the response feeds into the property dashboard alongside the maintenance request log, giving managers a same-day indicator of guest experience that complements the longer-form review cycle of platforms like TripAdvisor. This took three weeks to build and required adding Twilio to the stack.",
    "The general manager has since shared the platform's existence with the Queensland Tourism Industry Council's small operator network, and we've had inquiries from two other small hotel groups in Queensland as a result. We are exploring a productised version of the rostering and maintenance modules that could be deployed more quickly for similar-sized operators without requiring a full custom build."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "In the first full quarter of operation, the group's property managers collectively reclaimed more than 12 hours per week that had been spent on manual roster preparation, shift change communications, and timesheet transcription. Payroll errors — which had been a source of staff tension and administrative rework — dropped sharply as digital timesheet records replaced handwritten ones. The maintenance response time improvement was the most visible quality-of-service change, and the general manager cited it as a direct contributor to an improvement in online guest review sentiment in the six months following launch.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "52%", label: "Reduction in scheduling time", context: "Across all three properties and property managers" },
    { value: "89%", label: "Reduction in payroll errors", context: "Compared to prior six-month period with manual timesheets" },
    { value: "47 min", label: "Avg maintenance response time", context: "Down from 4.2 hours average before the platform" },
    { value: "96%", label: "Shift swaps resolved same-day", context: "Up from an untracked but estimated 40% under WhatsApp system" },
    { value: "85/85", label: "Staff active on app", context: "All 85 staff onboarded within 2 weeks of their property going live" },
    { value: "1 view", label: "All three properties in one dashboard", context: "GM previously needed 30–45 minutes of calls to get this picture" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
